node.title: Estimated Memory Needed
node.bodyText:
Is there a way within a MOOSE app to do some memory estimation ahead of the simulation? In ansys runs it will calculate the memory needed for a solve to fit entirely in memory or if it needs to switch to writing to disk for the simulation.
What I have run into is simulations that will start in a configuration on the HPC and exit with code 9, which I believe is an out of memory error. Sometimes when I adjust the configuration to use less cpus per node and more nodes to get more memory the solve will run. Other times it will still not solve and still exit with an error code 9.
It would be nice if I could get an estimate during the MOOSE setup where it determines how much memory it thinks it will need so that I can determine if the solve was never going to work or if there was potentially a memory leak somewhere.

Hello
We do not have that implemented. You can get a view of the current memory expenditure from the perf graph live print.
Code 9 is indeed OOM.
Reducing the number of processes, using distributed meshes, removing auxiliary fields that are not needed are all good ways to reduce the memory footprint rapidly. For further improvements, you'll want to work on the preconditioning cost most of the time.

or if there was potentially a memory leak somewhere.

if you have a cluster with valgrind installed, it should be fairly easy to detect most memory leaks with that.
We should write this down as a feature request. I think we can get a ball park estimate fairly easily, but it wont be very accurate without a lot of work interfacing with petsc to predict its needs
Guillaume
Ok thanks...is there a place to do the feature request?

You can try Debug/show_actions=true, which will print memory usage at the beginning of each action (or setup stage). Particular attention should be given on init_problem task, where memory for solution vectors is allocated. If your Executioner/solve_type is a type other than JFNK, memory for preconditioning matrix will be allocated at its first evaluation (after MOOSE prints residual norm of the first linear iteration I believe). You can estimate memory usage of the matrix based on the number of unknowns of the nonlinear system printed by MOOSE. There could be other places of heavy memory usage depending on your application.
Github issues are the place for feature requests.

node.bodyText:

[grain_1_IC]
type = SpecifiedSmoothCircleIC
variable = 'gr0 gr1 gr2'

y_positions = '50.0 50.0 50.0'

[]
So the idea is to initialize several new grains in a geometry and want each of them to be with a different euler angle and independent from each other.
Thanks in advance!

Hello
I think this is definitely doable programmatically. Input file wise not sure,
What error are you getting exactly ?
Guillaume

It says:
*** ERROR ***
The following error occurred in the object "MOOSE Problem", of type "FEProblem".
Variable 'gr0 gr1 gr2' requested in initial condition 'grain_1_IC' does not exist.

I think you need to use the related action that creates variables as well as the IC. (I think they do that I ll check tomorrow)
Check out some example inputs for the ICs in phase field

As @GiudGiud mentioned, it is not supported for multiple variables. Each IC can only assign the value to a single variable. You can use three IC blocks to assign the ICs to gr0, gr1 and gr2 separately.

node.title: PorousFlow EnthalpySink depreciated?
node.bodyText:
Hi all,
I've been wondering if EnthalpySink has been removed from PF. I need to run some simulations with complex well geometries, and in the past, I would rely on EnthalpySink for this purpose. However, it seems that it's no longer available.
Is there an alternative option? Perhaps PorousFlowLineSink? The issue with PorousFlowLineSink is that it lacks the T_in flag, so I can't fix the temperature I want to inject.
Does anyone have any suggestions or workarounds?
Thanks
It's still there isn't it?

Hi Chris,
Sorry I got confused. I remember that there was a PolyLineSink which could also had T_in as flag. Here an example with Falcon:
https://github.com/idaholab/falcon/blob/devel/examples/rtes_htm/Cranfield_HTM_continous_season_caps_water_newboundary_coarse.i
Where there is a formulation as

    type = FunctionEnthalpySink
    fluid_phase = 0
    variable = temperature
    SumQuantityUO = heat_enthalpy_in_inc
    line_base = '1 -9.99 -9.99 3.6'
    line_length = ${well_length}
    line_direction = '0 0 1'
    pressure = porepressure
    function = T_inj_function
    fp = tabulated_water
    p_or_t_vals = '-1e9 1e9'
    fluxes = '-${inj_ext_flux} -${inj_ext_flux}'


Should be in PorousFlow, right?
Is PorousFlowEnthalpySink.C functionally equivalent?

Hi Chris,
Well... is not quite the same...
Looks like PorousFlowEnthalpySink is a boundary condition and not a DiracKernel.
I guess the difference is that I need to define it as a BC and therefore I need to have nodesets at the injection points, which complicates things a bit when the mesh is generated.
I can try to modify PorousFlowLineSink to include T_in to inject enthalpy at certain temperature.
Let me know if that worth to try :)
Cheers!

node.title: Inconsistency in Values of AuxVariables after Transfer using MultiAppCopyTransfer
node.bodyText:
Dear moose experts,
I am writing to address an issue with numerical inconsistency during the transfer of an AuxVariable named df_elastic_dgr0 from a sub-cp case to a main-pf case within our multi-app case.
Specifically, I have initiated a multi-app scenario, comprising 02_parent_pf.i and 02_sub_cp.i. The objective is to facilitate the transfer of the MaterialProperty df_elastic/dgr0 from the sub-cp simulation to the main-pf simulation. To execute this, I initially utilized the auxkernel MaterialRealAux within the sub-cp simulation to generate the auxVariable df_elastic_dgr0. Subsequently, employing the MultiAppCopyTransfer, I transferred df_elastic_dgr0 to the main-pf simulation. Despite sharing the identical name, df_elastic_dgr0, it has come to my attention that there exists a discrepancy between the values of df_elastic_dgr0 observed in the sub-cp and main-pf simulations, as illustrated in the attached figure.

This discrepancy is concerning and may indicate an issue either in the configuration of the MultiAppCopyTransfer or in the handling of the AuxVariable within the simulations. I would greatly appreciate any insights, advice, or examples you can provide to help me address this challenge effectively. Your expertise in this matter is invaluable, and your guidance will significantly impact the success of my project.
Thank you in advance for your time and support. I look forward to your response and guidance.
Best regards,
Wei

Hello
If the meshes are identical and the variables also of the same finite element type, then you can try other transfers.
MultiAppGeneralFieldNearesLocation and ShapeEvaluation transfer should both give you the same result (if the variable is constant monomial or a first order Lagrange for NearestLocation, any variable for ShapeEvaluation).
When is the transfer executed? And when is the output performed? Which time step are we looking at?
Are you using block restriction or any other more advanced parameters to the transfer?
Guillaume

Dear Guillaume,
First and foremost, I would like to express my gratitude for your suggestions and assistance, Following your advice, we successfully resolved the issue we were facing by using MultiAppGeneralFieldNeastLocationTransfer. Additionally, we observed that the use of the interval parameter in the outputs module significantly affects the comparison of output results.
Thank you once again for your guidance, which has been crucial to the progress of our projects.
Best wishes!!
wei
